Title: Moonlight | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment: I remember when I first saw Moonlight in theaters, and I ended up HATING IT! But as time went by, and the more I thought about it; the more I began to appreciate it. This movie isn't good solely because the main character is a black gay man; this movie is good because of how it was structured compared to most Hollywood films. Like Quentin Tarantino, and Stanley Kubrick before him, Barry Jenkins offered an entirely different three-act structure that exploits the life of Chiron; with each act basically telling its own story. I believe films like Moonlight will gain an impact to film scholars the same way Pulp Fiction and 2001 did. My only problem with this movie is that the third act dragged a bit longer than the other two; but overall, I now understand why Moonlight is a Best Picture winner.

rating 2/5

MY HOPE FOR GOOD QUALITY HOLLYWOOD FILMS IS RESTORED

Title: Moonlight | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment: I haven't seen La La Land yet, but I pray it's better than Moonlight. The movie was boring, and nauseating with its endless camera turns and jump cuts. It's not like I got lost-- I knew what was going on at every moment and the movie was predictable as shit-- it just hurt to watch. The camera was irritatingly jumpy, even in scenes without action, and I know _why_ they shot it like that; but I think the movie would've felt just as dramatic without the blatantly documentary-ish effects.¬†In my opinion, this movie was no different or groundbreaking than "Precious" or "Coach Carter" or "Training Day", or any other successful film that focused on people of color. In fact, the only question I ended up asking myself wasn't, "Why did it win best picture?" Rather, I asked myself why it won¬†_any_¬†awards at all. It's just a recycled trope and story that's been adapted a thousand times over. Every year a movie like this comes out and every year it wins a truck full of rewards, for no legitimate reason besides "oh look, it's an all-black cast"!¬†If I didn't know it was award winning, I would've thought it was an independent, b-movie film. The only interesting element was seeing Chiron's interaction with the kid and realising the endless cycle it created. But again, this has been done¬†_to death_. Overall, I'd give this movie a 5/10. I hope La La Land is at least an 8.

Comment:
I do want to understand even though I will not be watching.  Understanding is key for me.  I found comments in this review helpful:  To insist that stories about poor, oppressed or otherwise marginal groups of people are really about everyone can be a way of denying their specificity. The universe is far too granular and far too vast for any one of us to comprehend, and Mr. Jenkins is far too disciplined a filmmaker to turn his characters into symbols.

He does not generalize. He empathizes.  

And perhaps the most beautiful thing about ‚ÄúMoonlight‚Äù is its open-endedness, its resistance to easy summary or categorization. I guess I‚Äôm back where I started, trying to decide what this movie is about. As with any original and challenging work, the answer may take a while to emerge, but what strikes me now is less the pain of Chiron‚Äôs circumstances than the sense that, in spite of everything, he is free. A bullied, neglected and all-but-silent child, he grows toward an understanding of himself and his world, and though it is agonizing to witness his progress, it is also thrilling. To be afforded a window into another consciousness is a gift that only art can give. To know Chiron is a privilege.

Comment:
The moment when Chiron is grown up and talking to his mom in rehab, when he counters her pleas with so much hostility, reminded me so much of my cousin who despises his crackhead mother for all the emotional abuse she put him through, and the effects are apparent. This was the first time in my entire life that a moment in a film brought me to tears, and I am a straight pacific islander who grew up in conditions not at all comparable to the ones in this film.

You can disagree with the agenda of this movie all you want, but let me tell you that moments in this film will hit you, no matter what your background is. You must suspend disbelief an judge this film with an objective point of view and understand its artistic value rather than immediately deferring to judgement.

Comment:
Okay, I LOVED this film! It's a film that ages like fine wine, tbh. I went to see it with a friend and the more we talked about the film and the imagery, the more that we appreciated every turn the movie took. I do have some qualms with the film, but it's not even really a qualm because all I wanted was more of the movie. I legit would watch another hour of this film because ugh, the color scheme, the ACTING, it's all superb.

I really related to Ashton Sanders' story and the acting in Act ll. The scene in the principals office had me choking up. [SPOILER] If Black had broken down in that moment, I would've been sobbing in the movie theater. I was hella choked up and bye yes were brimming with tears. Ashton played an emotional constipated and fragile teen so well. There was so much emotion in his eyes and ugh, I could go on and on <3

Comment: i am in a true dilemma!! i saw moonlight last night but i didn't really enjoy it??? i really wanted to, but i didn't really see why it was so groundbreaking. the music and cinematography were breathtaking (the shot of little in the bathtub, juan n little in the ocean, bloody chiron at the sink, kevin smoking in the diner, i gasped with delight) but the plot was so weak and empty. jenkins seemed to delve in the quieter moments but there was no excitement to contrast- i feel like i would of been able to skip to the end without missing any information. the acting was absolutely stellar and felt very organic, but i just think how the character of chiron was handled wasn't great- he was only portrayed in a way to make me feel sorry for him and i didn't emotionally connect with his character at all. i don't want this to deter anyone from seeing the movie, but i really need to know if anyone felt the same way, because i really don't understand why it is getting so much oscar buzz- its definitely not a bad film, but it's not BRILLIANT, and i feel like i am going to forget about it in a few weeks. if anyone thought it was brilliant please tell me why, perhaps there is some metaphorical meaning or something that i am missing?

I hated the ending because the movie took you past coming of age but left you in what appeared to be adulthood going no where.  Let me say, I saw it without knowing anything of what it was about.  To me, it was not a Gay movie until the end and I am not even sure it was then.  What I saw was a young boy being bullied because he was small, dressed differently, and had more of a responsible attitude.  I saw a mother keep telling the boy how much she loved him but she wasn't willing to make the change needed to show him love.  I saw a boy discovering and experiencing sex.  I saw a boy sharing love (not sex) from another boy that was set in the same environment.  I saw one boy give in to the crime life that would most likely send him back to prison whereas the other boy realized his mistakes and focused on making a new life for himself.  The acting was good. Comment:
One of the weakest films this season.
1. Acting is really average and competent without any stand-out performance at all. This is unlike "Captain Fantastic" and "Fences" when the whole cast did well.
2. This is obviously a shameful Oscar bait. African American poverty, drugs, homosexuality, coming-of-age, broken family. What more do you need to complete the stereotype?
3. Does it add anything new to the discussion on these issues? Nope.
4. Poor pacing. It used to be innovative for draggy and slow pacing to add the necessary shine to art-house films. But that was in the late 1990s. Get over it.
5. You sort of expect something to happen throughout the movie. But nothing ever did. The last scene is really pretentious and could really be edited significantly.

Title: Moonlight | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment:
This is truly one of the greatest films ever made. That's a bold statement but it's¬† deserving. It is perfection filmmaking by Barry Jenkins. The performances across the board where outstanding. Everyone's performance felt real and genuine. Mahershala Ali and Naomi Harris really steal the show in the supporting cast along with Janelle Mon√°e. And as for the six actors who played Chiron and Kevin, kid, teen, or adult, they all were perfect. The film also had an amazing script, jaw dropping cinematography, and a haunting score. The characters were rich and complex and felt like they were real people. The film is filled with realism and often is very hard to watch but at the same time it is so captivating and you can't take your eyes off the screen. Even the little details were perfect. The lighting, sound mixing, editing,¬† visual metaphors, and character details were so thought out and meaningful. The films plot is simple but effective. We've seen films where we watch the main character grow up in front of our eyes such as Boyhood but it's done with such class here that is gives off a completely fresh and new feel. The way the film is broken up into three chapters also gave it an interesting spin. The chapters are broken up nearly ten years apart so us the audience has to piece some things together in order to understand the development of the characters. The atmosphere also gives it this unique feeling. It's beautiful but very haunting and it really stays with you. Miami (where the film takes place) feels like a character. Not to mention the movie has not only a fantastic score but some of the best uses of music in any movie particularly during the third chapter which also has one of the best scenes in any film of the past decade. There are so many little nuances and things to talk about for hours after the viewing. On its surface it may not be relatable to many people but when you break it down it has something that anyone could grab onto. Whether you've had a tough time growing up, living in poverty, being homosexual, being bullied, not having a father figure, having a parent who is addicted to drugs, self discovery, becoming someone you're not, being different, covering yourself up, standing up for yourself, accepting forgiveness, or being a human being. This is a human story.¬† It's absolutely mesmerizing. Beautiful, brilliant, poetic, sad but uplifting. It is perfect in length and never gets boring. It doesn't drag and ends leaving you asking questions and wanting more. Needing to experience it again. It's subject matter is important but it never tries to beat you over the head with it. It leaves you speechless. It does something that true art should do and that is leave you having discussions. MOONLIGHT is a MASTERPIECE. 

Score:10/10

Title: Moonlight | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment: I saw this movie on the same day as I saw "Arrival. It was maybe two or three days after the election and both screenings were packed. A rarity for films that are not blockbusters. Okay, one had spaceships and aliens in them but it was not filled with big battle scenes and focused mostly on learning how to speak the aliens language. Yet both films had the audiences full attention. On the surface, they seem almost nothing alike, and yet they are so similar. They both encourage empathy in a time when it does not seem to be encouraged, and like "Arrival" "Moonlight" was more interested in tension and possibility than explosive moments. After the election, many people were confused, angry and afraid and hopefully when they left they felt a little less so. I know I did. I went into BOTH movies knowing almost nothing about them but I will carry that experience with me, the sharing of an emotional journey with a group of strangers through a compelling story (twice), for the rest of my life.

Comment: It looks phenomenal. You can never win with or at least make some people happy. This is a film trying to shed light on sexuality by bashing down the stereotypical barriers and at the same time trying to correctly convey a certain location and how those inhabitants are affected by it and those around them. I seen someone say something about all black people's morals being affected by Christian faith and I think that basically says that other races' outlook on homosexuality isn't and I think that's racist within itself, even if that's not the intention of the statement. In fact, most reasons why homophobia is rampant still to this day by all races is because it stems from religious beliefs. You think white people aren't raised to live by outdated ideas about masculinity? You don't any kid, regardless of race is safe from being subjected from bullying via homophobic actions? While I cannot speak for the black race myself for obvious reasons, I've had a few different black friends (a term I hate to use but makes sense for this argument) that say that they know more "down low" black men with gfs/wives/kids than they do of other races. That may be an outrageous statement to some, but in my area there is truth in it, even if it's not completely accurate. I know several gay or trans black men from either work or mutual friends, and IF the black community is harder on their homosexual men than other races, I truly feel sorry for those people. I work with a pair of black twins, one of which is gay. The heterosexual brother and other members of their family beat him down physically simply bc he came out. Maybe this film without relying on flamboyant stereotypical gay men, can really say something about those black men and that's quite alright. But to say others aren't pressured into keeping their secret to themselves without fear of persecution by loved ones is the silliest thing I've seen all day. Sorry for the long rant, if you're still reading at this point lol.

Comment:
A deeply compelling trailer.
The initial viewing of this trailer took my fucking breath away. I don't think I've seen anything like this--handled with such care--before in mainstream film. Finally what appears to be a central filmic narrative focusing on the harrowing sexual development of a beautiful dark skin black boy's journey into manhood. There are scenes that look brutal tough, because...well the subject matter is tough. Yet I'm hoping what we'll also see for this character in his journey, is the love and hard-won affirmation that is so desperately needed as powerful and redemptive representation for QPOC and black folks as a whole! (sigh) I'm really rooting for this, and can't wait to see it!
